In the following year, 118, he advocated in the popular interest⁶ the proposition for the founding of a colony at Narbo Martius in Gallia Transalpina, recently subdued, and, notwithstanding the opposition of the Senate, carried his proposal,⁷ and received himself the commission to found the colony. Less successful was his defense, in 113 13.c., of the Vestal Licinia, accused of unchastity, who with several* other Vestals was condemned.⁸

Four years later (109) Crassus filled the quaestorship in Asia, and had intercourse there, as well as at Athens, on his return with the most renowned philosophers and teachers of rhetoric of that time.⁹
